{
  "texts": [
    "Note that since ∂Q is not quite a smooth manifold, the map Tan ∂Q is only defined on the interior of each face, in particular σ-a.e.",
    "We recall the Stokes theorem:Q dω = ∂Q ω.",
    "In particular, if ω = π 1 dπ 2 ∧ • • • ∧ dπ d for some smooth functions π 1,..., π d, then dω = dπ 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dπ d. The above equality of Stokes reads in this case asQ det Dπ dL d = ∂Q π 1 ⟨dπ 2 ∧ • • • ∧ dπ d, Tan ∂Q ⟩ dσ.",
    "(2.4) Functional-analytic structure of Lipschitz mapsGiven any metric space X with a distinguished point 0 ∈ X, we use the notation(i) Lip 0 (X) = {f: X → R: f (0) = 0 and f is Lipschitz}, (ii) Lip b (X) = {f: X → R: f is Lipschitz and bounded}.The considerations below for the space Lip 0 (X) follow from the book of Weaver [43,Chapter 3].",
    "The space Lip b (X) may be identified with a Lip 0 (Y) space (over some metric space Y) via [43,Corollary 2.14]."
  ]
}